text=>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary:a history lesson of how women got the right to vote in the US%0aParent:(Main.)CommunityAndGovernment%0aIncludeMe:[[(Main.)CommunityAndGovernment]]%0aCategories:[[!Articles]]%0aTags: voting right, feminism%0a(:tags-hide voting right, feminism :)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a[-''(This came in an email 11 September 2004)''-]%0a%0a!!Subject: History Lesson %0a%0aPlease Read This..it is very Important.  Republican or Democrat...It %0adoes not matter. This is not partisan. %0a%0a>>quote%3c%3c%0a!! How Women Got The Right to Vote %0a%0aA short history lesson on the privilege of voting... %0aThe women were innocent and defenseless. And by the end of the night, %0athey were barely alive. Forty prison guards wielding clubs and their %0awarden's blessing went on a rampage against the 33 women wrongly convicted of %0a"obstructing sidewalk traffic." %0a%0aThey beat Lucy Burn, chained her hands to the cell bars above her head %0aand left her hanging for the night, bleeding and gasping for air. They %0ahurled Dora Lewis into a dark cell, smashed her head against an iron bed and %0aknocked her out cold. Her cellmate, Alice Cosu, thought Lewis was dead %0aand suffered a heart attack. Additional affidavits describe the guards %0agrabbing, dragging, beating, choking, slamming, pinching, twisting and %0akicking the women. %0a%0aThus unfolded the "Night of Terror" on Nov. 15, 1917, when the warden %0aat the Occoquan Workhouse in Virginia ordered his guards to teach a %0alesson to the suffragists imprisoned there because they dared to picket %0aWoodrow Wilson's White House for the right to vote. %0a%0aFor weeks, the women's only water came from an open pail. Their %0afood--all of it colorless slop--was infested with worms. When one of the leaders, %0aAlice Paul, embarked on a hunger strike, they tied her to a chair, %0aforced a tube down her throat and poured liquid into her until she vomited. %0aShe was tortured like this for weeks until word was smuggled out to the %0apress. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aSo, refresh my memory.  Some women won't vote this year because--why, %0aexactly? We have  carpool duties? We have to get to work? Our vote %0adoesn't matter? It's raining? %0a%0aLast week, I went to a sparsely attended screening of HBO's new movie %0a"Iron Jawed Angels."  It is a graphic depiction of the battle these %0awomen waged so that I could pull the curtain at the polling booth and %0ahave my say.  I am ashamed to say I needed the reminder. %0a%0aAll these years later, voter registration is still my passion. But the %0aactual act of voting had become less personal for me, more rote. %0aFrankly, voting often felt more like an obligation than a privilege. Sometimes %0ait was inconvenient. %0a%0aMy friend Wendy, who is my age and studied women's history, saw the HBO %0amovie, too. When she stopped by my  desk to talk about it, she looked %0aangry. She was angry--angry with herself.  "One thought kept coming %0aback to me as I watched that movie," she said.  "What would those women %0athink of the way I use--or don't use--my right to vote?  All of us take it %0afor granted now, not just younger women." The right to  vote, she said, had %0abecome valuable to her "all over again." %0a%0aHBO will run the movie periodically before releasing it on video and %0aDVD. I wish all history, social studies and government teachers would %0ainclude the movie in their curriculum. I want it shown on Bunko night, too, and %0aanywhere else women gather. I realize this isn't our usual idea of %0asocializing, but we are not voting in the numbers that we should be, %0aand I think a little shock therapy is in order. %0a%0aIt is jarring to watch Woodrow Wilson and his cronies try to persuade a %0apsychiatrist to declare Alice Paul insane so that she could be %0apermanently institutionalized.  And it is inspiring to watch the doctor refuse. %0aAlice Paul was strong, he said, and brave. That didn't make her crazy. %0aThe doctor admonished the men: "Courage in women is often mistaken for %0ainsanity." %0a%0aPlease pass this on to all the women you know.  We need to get out and %0avote and use this right that was fought so hard for by these very %0acourageous women. %0a%0a%0a%0a%0a
