unger strike, they tied her to a chair, %0a%3c forced a tube down her throat and poured liquid into her until she vomited. %0a%3c She was tortured like this for weeks until word was smuggled out to the %0a%3c press. %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c So, refresh my memory.  Some women won't vote this year because--why, %0a%3c exactly? We have  carpool duties? We have to get to work? Our vote %0a%3c doesn't matter? It's raining? %0a%3c %0a%3c Last week, I went to a sparsely attended screening of HBO's new movie %0a%3c "Iron Jawed Angels."  It is a graphic depiction of the battle these %0a%3c women waged so that I could pull the curtain at the polling booth and %0a%3c have my say.  I am ashamed to say I needed the reminder. %0a%3c %0a%3c All these years later, voter registration is still my passion. But the %0a%3c actual act of voting had become less personal for me, more rote. %0a%3c Frankly, voting often felt more like an obligation than a privilege. Sometimes %0a%3c it was inconvenient. %0a%3c %0a%3c My friend Wendy, who is my age and studied women's history, saw the HBO %0a%3c movie, too. When she stopped by my  desk to talk about it, she looked %0a%3c angry. She was angry--angry with herself.  "One thought kept coming %0a%3c back to me as I watched that movie," she said.  "What would those women %0a%3c think of the way I use--or don't use--my right to vote?  All of us take it %0a%3c for granted now, not just younger women." The right to  vote, she said, had %0a%3c become valuable to her "all over again." %0a%3c %0a%3c HBO will run the movie periodically before releasing it on video and %0a%3c DVD. I wish all history, social studies and government teachers would %0a%3c include the movie in their curriculum. I want it shown on Bunko night, too, and %0a%3c anywhere else women gather. I realize this isn't our usual idea of %0a%3c socializing, but we are not voting in the numbers that we should be, %0a%3c and I think a little shock therapy is in order. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is jarring to watch Woodrow Wilson and his cronies try to persuade a %0a%3c psychiatrist to declare Alice Paul insane so that she could be %0a%3c permanently institutionalized.  And it is inspiring to watch the doctor refuse. %0a%3c Alice Paul was strong, he said, and brave. That didn't make her crazy. %0a%3c The doctor admonished the men: "Courage in women is often mistaken for %0a%3c insanity." %0a%3c %0a%3c Please pass this on to all the women you know.  We need to get out and %0a%3c vote and use this right that was fought so hard for by these very %0a%3c courageous women. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a
